**Abstract:**
Oncolytic viruses have emerged as a promising modality in cancer treatment, and the oncolytic reovirus (ORV) has shown considerable potential in selectively targeting and eliminating cancer cells while sparing healthy tissues. This review aims to provide a comprehensive overview of the current state of research on ORV, including its mechanisms of action, safety and efficacy in preclinical and clinical trials, and the challenges and future directions in the development of ORV-based cancer therapies.

**Introduction:**
Cancer remains a leading cause of mortality worldwide, and despite significant advancements in cancer treatment, there is still a pressing need for more effective and targeted therapies. Oncolytic viruses, which are engineered to selectively infect and kill cancer cells, have gained significant attention as a promising approach in cancer therapy. The oncolytic reovirus (ORV) is a naturally occurring virus that has demonstrated remarkable potential in targeting and eliminating cancer cells, while leaving healthy cells intact.

**Mechanisms of ORV-Mediated Oncolysis:**
ORV induces cancer cell death through a multifaceted mechanism, involving apoptosis, necrosis, and autophagy. The virus selectively targets cancer cells with activated Ras signaling pathways, a common feature in many types of cancer. Upon infection, ORV replicates within the cancer cell, leading to cell lysis and the release of new virus particles that can infect neighboring cancer cells, resulting in significant tumor regression and improved survival outcomes in cancer patients. The Ras/RalGEF/p38 pathway plays a crucial role in dictating host cell permissiveness to reovirus infection, as evidenced by studies demonstrating the importance of this pathway in ORV-mediated oncolysis.

**Preclinical and Clinical Trials:**
Preclinical studies have consistently demonstrated the safety and efficacy of ORV in various cancer models, including breast, lung, colon, and brain cancer. Clinical trials have also been conducted to evaluate the safety and efficacy of ORV in cancer patients. A Phase I trial of ORV in patients with advanced cancer demonstrated that the virus was well-tolerated and exhibited evidence of anti-tumor activity. Furthermore, a Phase II trial of ORV in combination with chemotherapy in patients with metastatic breast cancer showed improved progression-free survival and overall survival compared to chemotherapy alone, highlighting the potential of ORV as a complementary therapy.

**Challenges and Future Directions:**
Despite the promising results of ORV-based cancer therapies, several challenges need to be addressed, including the development of resistance to the virus, potential toxicity, and the need for more effective delivery methods. Future research directions include the development of combination therapies that combine ORV with other anti-cancer agents, such as chemotherapy and radiation therapy, as well as the use of ORV as a vehicle for delivering anti-cancer genes to cancer cells. Additionally, investigations into the potential of ORV to stimulate anti-tumor immune responses and enhance the efficacy of immunotherapies are warranted.

**Conclusion:**
The oncolytic reovirus (ORV) represents a promising novel therapeutic agent in cancer treatment, with significant potential for selectively targeting and eliminating cancer cells while sparing healthy tissues. While further research is necessary to fully realize the potential of ORV-based cancer therapies, the current state of research suggests that ORV may become a valuable addition to the arsenal of cancer therapies in the future. Continued investigations into the mechanisms of ORV-mediated oncolysis, combination therapies, and delivery methods will be crucial in unlocking the full therapeutic potential of ORV.

